Git :
    - Git is free and open source version control system and source code management
        and software configuration management
    - git --version: to check version of git in cmd

Why Git:
    - Developers can work together from anywhere in the world.
    - Developers can see the full history of the project.
    - Developers can revert to earlier versions of a project

Git Uses:
    - Tracking code changes
    - Tracking who made change
    - coding collaboration
    - manage code with repositories(directory)
    - "Clone" a project to work on a local copy(computer)
    - Control and track changes with staging and committing
    - Branch and merge to allow for a work on different parts
        and versions of a project
    - pull the latest version of the project to a local copy
    - push local updates to the main project

GitHub :
    Github is a platform to host source code of application that work with help of git commands

git status : shows  all of the files that are updated , deleted modified that are not saved in commit yet
git add . : takes all modified files in your working directory and places the modified version in a staging area
get add filename
git add filename filename 

git commit - m : commit files in git repository 

Directory - folder
cd - change directory
git clone repository_address = Bring a repository that is hosted somewhere like github into a folder on your local machine
add = track your files and changes in git
commit =  save files in git
push = upload git commits to a remote repo like github
pull = download changes from remote repo to your local machine the opposite of push
la = ls -la (list everything in the directory including hidden files)
.md = markdown



